      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Porphyry</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Porphyry</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/442</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">433</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="337-338"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/684</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Greek author and Neoplatonist.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(<abbr>ca.</abbr> 232 – <abbr>ca.</abbr> 305)</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Greek author and Neoplatonist. Of Porphyry’s many writings only his immensely
                        influential Introduction (<hi rend="italic">Eisagoge</hi>) to <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Aristotle">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/342">Aristotle</persName>
                        </ref>’s ‘Organon’ (logical works) was translated into Syriac.
                        Two versions survive, the first, anonymous, made in the early 6th <abbr>cent.</abbr>, and
                        the second, in the form of a revision by <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Athanasios-II-of-Balad">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/109">Athanasios of
                            Balad</persName>
                        </ref> made in 645. Commentaries on his Introduction by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Proba">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/686">Proba</persName>
                        </ref>,
                            <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Dionysios-bar-Salibi">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/212">Dionysios
                            bar Ṣalibi</persName>
                        </ref>, and <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Yawsep-II">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/813">Yawsep II</persName>
                        </ref>
                        survive.</p>
                    <p>In two of his works Porphyry draws on a lost work by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Bardaisan">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/3">Bardaiṣan</persName>
                        </ref> on the
                        Indian Brahmans (‘On Abstinence’ IV.17, and at greater length, ‘On the
                        Styx’, in <hi rend="italic">Porphyrius</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Fragmenta,</hi> 
                  <abbr>ed.</abbr> A. Smith [1993], 376F). Porphyry, who calls
                        Bardaiṣan both a ‘Babylonian’ and ‘from Mesopotamia’, mentions that he had
                        acquired this knowledge from an Indian embassy of <abbr>ca.</abbr> 218 to the emperor
                        Elagabalus.</p>
                </div>
